          "explanation": "CT imaging of acute head trauma is performed to detect treatable lesions before secondary neurologic damage occurs. CT is highly accurate for the detection of acute intra and extra-axial hemorrhage, as well as skull, temporal bone, facial, and orbital fractures.CT is considered the gold standard for detecting calcification. In MRI, calcification appears with various signal intensities on conventional spin echo (SE) T1 or T2 weighted images, which makes it difficult to identify definitively as calcium.",
